args:
The mystery man from earlier arrives to buoy
the dejected prince's spirits. He names himself
Audric, an acquaintance of Aurelius who acts as
a proxy for the feelings the king held for his son
at a young age. Meanwhile, Zethia awakens in
darkness to face a surprising figure.

Confirming decrease in surrounding
mana concentration.
▷Keep it up, both of you! The barrier
is weakening!◁
Is my darling going to be all right?
I think he's in shock. And really, who can\nblame him? I can't imagine having my\nsister vanish in front of me AGAIN.
Look, the boss is gonna be fine, yeah?\nHe's been through worse than this and\npicked himself up off the floor every time.
We're making fine progress thanks to the\ncombined work of Zena and Sheila.
Good. And what of the prince?
He remains alone—although that man\nheaded his way a little while ago.
Gatov, that man looks exactly like...
He's a dead ringer for the man when he\nwas younger. It's like we're seeing a ghost.
Perhaps this tree simply transcends all\nhuman understanding.
Oh, it's you. Thank you for helping\nus earlier.
Without you, we wouldn't have survived.
There is no need to thank me. The more\npressing issue is that which clearly weighs\nupon your mind now.
I couldn't rescue my sister—again.\nThis is the third time I've failed.
She claimed she's been spirited away\nto the past and told some kind of truth,\nand then she actually helped Nedrick!
What could she have learned? Did it have\nanything to do with what Finlorda said\nabout truth and history?
I don't know—and now I'll never know\nbecause I couldn't save her!
Is that what you ought to be thinking\nabout right now?
What else would I be thinking about?
Is now the time for doubt and confusion?\nFor being downcast and giving yourself\nover to regret?
It is only natural for past mistakes to\ncause pain and doubt.
But will things get better if you wallow in\nsuch distress? Will the future you seek\nsuddenly materialize before you?
What you ought to do right now is prepare\nfor your next course of action.
We have to stop Jinlorda and Nedrick.\nThat hasn't changed.
I'm worried sick about Zethia, but I have to\nset that aside and worry about them first.
At last, the light returns to your eyes!\nYou must endeavor never to forget how\nyou feel in this moment.
You're right, sir! I shall catch the both of\nthem and get Zethia back! I swear it!
You don't have to speak so formally to me.\nTreat me as you would any other comrade.
Oh, um...sorry. I couldn't help myself.\nYou're just such a dignified presence.
Which reminds me, I don't even know\nyour name.
Your father bade me come to your aid,\nand so I have.
Wait, so you're an acquaintance of my\nfather like Gatov?!
Something like that. Let it suffice to say\nthat I know your father well.
And while it will be only for a short time,\nI shall continue to travel with you.
Thank you. It would be most reassuring to\nhave someone like you close at hand.
It will be my pleasure.\nStill, you have truly...
Ah, forgive me. My mind became lost\nin the past for a moment.
Did you know me when I was little?\nDo you know where I truly come from?
In that case, do you mind sharing anything\nmy father may have said about me?
He wrote a letter claiming he'd left his\nthoughts behind here for me, but I haven't\nseen anything like that.
What did my father think about my being\nborn in the Faerie Kingdom?
Did you ever feel as though your father\ntreated you in a special fashion?
Special? No. I always felt he treated me\nin the same way he did all my siblings.

Sure, there were a lot of times he would
reprimand me for immature thoughts,
and he didn't hesitate to speak harshly
if he felt I needed it...
But he always had an open ear for my\nopinions—and he took them to heart.
Also, before things went awry in Alberia,\nhe respected my feelings as to why I\nhadn't undertaken the Dragon Choosing.
He treated me like my own person,\nnot just some progeny to follow his will.
I think he was trying to make sure I didn't\nrealize I was born different.
At first, he thought of you as different—it\ncould not be helped. By your very nature, \nyou took the place of his deceased child.
In addition, you bore the heavy burden of\nhaving a body which came from the flesh\nof the Other.
You were a child of his own selfishness,\nand he wanted to make your life good\nmore out of duty than anything else.
To that end, he swore to treat you no\ndifferently than his other children so you\nwould never feel wanting.
He was determined to do those things\nwhen he received you from Finlorda.\nHowever...
When he held you in his arms, all thoughts\nof duty and selfishness vanished.
The dozing child he held was a tiny life,\nno different from any of his other children.
How the child was born, the nature of his\nbody—these things were inconsequential.
He simply wanted the boy to be happy,\nand he knew then and there he would do\nwhatever he must to see this realized.
By the time he became aware of it, that\nfeeling was all that remained in his heart.
That is what Aurelius told me, and I\nremember it well.
Thank you for telling me of my father's\nfeelings in such detail, Audric.
...Not at all. In fact, I am the one who\nshould thank you.
You need not worry over it. Instead, simply\nkeep your disposition cheerful and focused\nas you ever have.
Your sister Zethia is not so far away\nfrom you yet.
Indeed. She is right here in the tree,\nyet in a different place at the same time.\nAs a result, we simply cannot see her.
Where am I? I can't see anything.\nI was in the sacred tree, and then...
You! What are you doing here?!
